Experimental

Introduction

The following are the events for the OpenJDK 21 (jdk-21.0.2+0, 16-January-2024), and Graal VM 23.1.1 (jdk-21.0.1) . The events are collected from the event configuration and the source code. Visit jfreventcollector for more information. this is also the place you can contribute additional event descriptions, if you don't want to contribute them directly to the OpenJDK. The site generator lives on GitHub too.

This page is maintained by Johannes Bechberger of the SapMachine team at SAP and contributors.

Some events have fake end times / durations, these are hidden in the event description here.

Flight Recorder

DumpReason

default profiling startTime 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Flight Recorder

Who requested the recording and why

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrEmergencyDump.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The DumpReason event in JFR provides information about the reason for writing recording data to disk. It is relevant to profiling as it allows users to understand why a dump occurred and which recording triggered it.

Fields:

  • reason: Reason for writing recording data to disk
  • recordingId: Id of the recording that triggered the dump, or -1 if it was not related to a recording

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
reason string Reason Reason for writing recording data to disk
recordingId int Recording Id Id of the recording that triggered the dump, or -1 if it was not related to a recording

DataLoss

default profiling startTime 11 17 21 22 23 graal vm

Category: Flight Recorder

Data could not be copied out from a buffer, typically because of contention

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrStorage.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The DataLoss event in JFR indicates the loss of recorded data. It is relevant for profiling and has the following fields:

  • amount: Represents the amount of data that was lost.
  • total: Represents the total amount of data lost for the thread.

The event is useful for profiling performance and identifying potential issues related to data loss during recording. By monitoring and analyzing this event, developers can gain insights into the amount of data being lost and take appropriate actions to optimize the recording process and prevent further data loss.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
amount ulong: bytes Amount Amount lost data
total ulong: bytes Total Total lost amount for thread

Flush

experimental startTime duration 14 17 21 22 23

Category: Flight Recorder

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrRecorderService.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The Flush event in JFR is an experimental event used for profiling purposes. It provides information about the flush operation, which is the process of writing data to disk.

The relevant fields of the Flush event are:

  • flushId: The identifier of the flush operation.
  • elements: The number of elements written during the flush operation.
  • size: The size of the data written during the flush operation.

The Flush event can be used to analyze the efficiency and performance of the flush operation in order to optimize the profiling process.

Configuration enabled threshold
default false 0 ns
profiling false 0 ns

Field Type Description
flushId ulong Flush Identifier
elements ulong Elements Written
size ulong: bytes Size Written

ActiveRecording

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ActiveRecordingEvent.java

Category: Flight Recorder

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ActiveRecordingEvent.java, PlatformRecorder.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ActiveRecording event in JFR is used for profiling and monitoring flight recordings. It provides information about an active recording session and its parameters. This event is relevant for profiling because it allows users to gather data on the current state and configuration of a running flight recording.

Fields of the ActiveRecording event include:

  • id: The ID of the recording session.
  • name: The name of the recording session.
  • destination: The destination of the recorded data.
  • disk: Indicates whether the recording is being written to disk.
  • maxAge: The maximum age of the recording before it is automatically discarded.
  • flushInterval: The interval at which recording data is flushed to disk.
  • maxSize: The maximum size of the recording data.
  • recordingStart: The start time of the recording session.
  • recordingDuration: The duration of the recording session.

By analyzing the values of these fields in the ActiveRecording event, users can gain insights into the current settings and parameters of a flight recording, allowing them to fine-tune their profiling and performance monitoring activities effectively.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
id long Id
name string Name Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
destination string Destination Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
disk boolean 21+ To Disk
maxAge long: millis Max Age
flushInterval long: millis 14+ Flush Interval
maxSize long: bytes Max Size
recordingStart long: epochmillis Start Time
recordingDuration long: millis Recording Duration

ActiveSetting

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ActiveSettingEvent.java

Category: Flight Recorder

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in EventControl.java, ActiveSettingEvent.java, PlatformRecorder.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ActiveSettingEvent is a JFR event that represents the current active setting in a recording configuration. It contains the following fields:

  • id: An identifier for the event.
  • name: The name of the setting.
  • value: The current value of the setting.

This event is relevant to profiling because it allows users to monitor and analyze the active settings during runtime. By capturing this event, users can understand which settings are in effect at different points in the application's execution and how they might impact performance or behavior.

In the given code context, the ActiveSettingEvent is used to write the active settings of an event control to a JFR recording. The writeActiveSettingEvent method iterates over the named controls of an event control, checks if the control is visible and enabled, and then retrieves and commits the active setting event with the current timestamp, event type ID, control name, and value.

Overall, the ActiveSettingEvent is a crucial component in profiling and monitoring JFR recordings, allowing users to gain insights into the active settings of a recording configuration.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
id long Event Id
name string Setting Name
value string Setting Value

JVM

JVMInformation

default profiling startTime duration endchunk 11 17 21 22 23 graal vm

Category: Java Virtual Machine

Description of JVM and the Java application

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JVMInformation event in JFR provides information about the JVM and the Java application being profiled. It includes the following fields:

  • jvmName: The name of the JVM being used.
  • jvmVersion: The version of the JVM being used.
  • jvmArguments: The command line arguments passed to the JVM.
  • jvmFlags: The settings file arguments used by the JVM.
  • javaArguments: The arguments passed to the Java application.
  • jvmStartTime: The time when the JVM was started.
  • pid: The process identifier of the JVM.

This event is useful for profiling and understanding the configuration of the JVM and the Java application being profiled. It provides important information about the runtime environment and settings, which can help in analyzing and optimizing the performance of the application.

Configuration enabled period
default true beginChunk
profiling true beginChunk

Field Type Description
jvmName string JVM Name
jvmVersion string JVM Version
jvmArguments string JVM Command Line Arguments
jvmFlags string JVM Settings File Arguments
javaArguments string Java Application Arguments
jvmStartTime long: epochmillis JVM Start Time
pid long Process Identifier

InitialSystemProperty

default profiling startTime endchunk 11 17 21 22 23 graal vm

Category: Java Virtual Machine

System Property at JVM start

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The InitialSystemProperty event in JFR represents the initial system properties set when the JVM starts up. It is relevant for profiling as it allows you to monitor and analyze the system properties that are used by the JVM during runtime.

Fields of the event:

  • key: represents the key of the system property.
  • value: represents the value of the system property.

To use this event for profiling:

  • Monitor the InitialSystemProperty event to gather information about the initial system properties set during JVM startup.
  • Analyze the values of the system properties to understand their impact on JVM performance and behavior.
  • Use this information to optimize the JVM configuration and identify potential bottlenecks or areas for improvement in your application.

Configuration enabled period
default true beginChunk
profiling true beginChunk

Field Type Description
key string Key
value string Value

  • ParallelGC

JVM: Class Loading

ClassLoad

startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Class Loading

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in systemDictionary.hpp, systemDictionaryShared.cpp, and systemDictionary.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ClassLoad event in JFR represents the loading of a class in the Java application. It provides relevant information for profiling, such as the loaded class, the defining class loader, and the initiating class loader. This event is useful for monitoring class loading activity in the application and analyzing the class loading behavior.

  • loadedClass: Represents the class that has been loaded.
  • definingClassLoader: Specifies the class loader that defined the loaded class.
  • initiatingClassLoader: Indicates the class loader that initiated the loading of the class.

Profiling tools can leverage the ClassLoad event to collect statistics on class loading patterns, identify potential performance bottlenecks related to class loading, and analyze the dependencies between class loaders.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default false true 0 ms
profiling false true 0 ms

Field Type Description
loadedClass Class Loaded Class Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
definingClassLoader ClassLoader Defining Class Loader Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
initiatingClassLoader ClassLoader Initiating Class Loader Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.

ClassDefine

startTime eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Class Loading

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in systemDictionary.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The EventClassDefine event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) is used for profiling and capturing information related to class definition in the JVM. It provides insights into the loading and defining of classes by different class loaders.

  • definedClass: Represents the class that has been defined or loaded.
  • definingClassLoader: Represents the class loader responsible for defining or loading the class.

This event is relevant for profiling because it allows developers to monitor and analyze the class loading process in the JVM. By capturing events of class definition, developers can gain insights into the performance and behavior of class loaders, identify any potential bottlenecks or issues in class loading, and optimize the overall class loading process.

profiling false true

ClassRedefinition

default profiling startTime 15 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Class Loading

The ClassRedefinition event in JFR captures information about the redefinition of a class. It is relevant to profiling as it provides insights into changes made to a class during runtime.

The fields of the ClassRedefinition event include:

  • redefinedClass: Represents the class that has been redefined.
  • classModificationCount: Indicates the number of times the class has been modified.
  • redefinitionId: Identifies the specific redefinition of the class.

By analyzing the ClassRedefinition event, profiling tools can track the changes made to a class and understand the impact of those changes on the application's performance and behavior.

The RedefineClasses event in JFR is used for class redefinition during profiling. It allows you to redefine multiple classes in a single operation, which can be useful for dynamically updating and modifying classes during runtime. The event has the following fields:

  • classCount: The number of classes being redefined.
  • redefinitionId: The unique identifier for the class redefinition.

This event is relevant for profiling because it enables you to make changes to classes at runtime without restarting the application. This can be useful for various profiling scenarios, such as hot code replacement or running experiments with different class versions.

JVM: Code Cache

CodeCacheFull

default profiling startTime eventThread 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Code Cache

A code heap is full, this leads to disabling the compiler

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in codeCache.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CodeCacheFull event in JFR represents a situation where a code heap is full and cannot accommodate any more code. It is relevant for profiling because it helps identify potential performance bottlenecks and allows for better resource management within the code cache.

Fields of the CodeCacheFull event:

  • codeBlobType: Specifies the type of code heap that is full.
  • startAddress: The starting address of the code heap.
  • commitedTopAddress: The committed top address of the code heap.
  • reservedTopAddress: The reserved top address of the code heap.
  • entryCount: The number of entries (code blobs) in the code heap.
  • methodCount: The number of methods present in the code heap.
  • adaptorCount: The number of adaptors present in the code heap.
  • unallocatedCapacity: The amount of unallocated capacity in the code heap.
  • fullCount: The count of how many times the code heap has become full.
  • codeCacheMaxCapacity: The maximum capacity of the code cache.

By analyzing the CodeCacheFull event, developers and profilers can determine the current state of the code cache and assess its efficiency. It allows for understanding code cache usage patterns, identifying potential optimizations, and making informed decisions to manage code cache resources effectively.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
codeBlobType CodeBlobType Code Heap Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
startAddress ulong: address Start Address
commitedTopAddress ulong: address Commited Top
reservedTopAddress ulong: address Reserved Top
entryCount int Entries
methodCount int Methods
adaptorCount int Adaptors
unallocatedCapacity ulong: bytes Unallocated
fullCount int Full Count
codeCacheMaxCapacity ulong: bytes 17+ Code Cache Maximum Capacity

CodeCacheStatistics

default profiling startTime everychunk 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Code Cache

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CodeCacheStatistics event in Java Flight Recorder (JFR) provides information about the code cache, which is used to store compiled code in the JVM. This event is relevant for profiling and performance analysis purposes. Here are the relevant fields of the event:

  • codeBlobType: Represents the type of code heap in the code cache.
  • startAddress: Indicates the start address of the code heap.
  • reservedTopAddress: Represents the top address reserved for the code heap.
  • entryCount: Indicates the number of entries in the code heap.
  • methodCount: Represents the number of methods stored in the code heap.
  • adaptorCount: Indicates the number of code adaptors in the code heap.
  • unallocatedCapacity: Represents the amount of unallocated capacity in the code heap.
  • fullCount: Indicates the number of times the code heap has become full.

By analyzing these fields, developers can gain insights into the utilization and performance of the code cache, identify potential bottlenecks, and optimize the compilation and execution of code in the JVM.

CodeCacheConfiguration

default profiling startTime endchunk 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Code Cache

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CodeCacheConfiguration event in JFR provides information about the configuration of the code cache in the Java Virtual Machine (JVM). It is relevant to profiling because it allows for monitoring and analyzing the memory usage and allocation within the code cache.

Fields:

  • initialSize: The initial size of the code cache.
  • reservedSize: The reserved size of the code cache.
  • nonNMethodSize: The size of the code heap for non-nmethod code.
  • profiledSize: The size of the code heap for profiled code.
  • nonProfiledSize: The size of the code heap for non-profiled code.
  • expansionSize: The size of the code cache expansion.
  • minBlockLength: The minimum block length in the code cache.
  • startAddress: The start address of the code cache.
  • reservedTopAddress: The reserved top address of the code cache.

The CodeCacheConfiguration event helps in analyzing and optimizing the memory usage of the code cache, which is crucial for improving the performance of the JVM. It can be used to monitor the growth and utilization of the code cache over time, detect potential memory-related issues, and make informed decisions regarding code cache configuration and tuning.

expansionSize ulong: bytes Expansion size
minBlockLength ulong: bytes Minimum Block Length

Compilation

default profiling startTime duration eventThread 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Compiler

Results of method compilation attempts

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in EventProvider.java, EmptyEventProvider.java, compilerEvent.hpp, compileBroker.cpp, and compilerEvent.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CompilationEvent is an event in the Java Flight Recorder (JFR) system that represents a compilation process performed by the JIT compiler. It contains information about the compilation, such as the compile identifier, compiler type, method being compiled, compilation level, whether the compilation succeeded or failed, the size of the compiled code, and the size of inlined code.

The fields of the CompilationEvent are:

  • compileId: the identifier of the compilation process
  • compiler: the type of compiler used for the compilation
  • method: the method being compiled
  • compileLevel: the level of compilation performed
  • succeeded: a flag indicating whether the compilation succeeded
  • isOsr: a flag indicating whether the compilation is an On Stack Replacement (OSR) compilation
  • codeSize: the size of the compiled code
  • inlinedBytes: the size of the inlined code

The CompilationEvent is useful for profiling and analyzing the performance of the JIT compiler. By collecting and analyzing these events, developers can gain insights into the compilation process and identify potential optimizations or performance bottlenecks in their code.

Configuration enabled threshold
default true 1000 ms
profiling true 100 ms

Field Type Description
compileId int Compilation Identifier
compiler CompilerType 14+ Compiler Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
method Method Method Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
compileLevel ushort Compilation Level
succeded boolean Succeeded
isOsr boolean On Stack Replacement
codeSize ulong: bytes Compiled Code Size
inlinedBytes ulong: bytes Inlined Code Size

The CompilerPhase event in JFR represents a compilation phase during profiling. It is relevant for profiling performance and understanding the compilation process.

  • phase field: Represents the specific compile phase that is being executed.
  • compileId field: Identifies the specific compilation process being profiled.

CompilationFailure

profiling startTime eventThread 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Compiler

In case a JIT compilation failed, a compilation failure is triggered, reporting the reason

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ciEnv.cpp, compilerEvent.hpp, and compilerEvent.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CompilationFailure event in JFR represents a failure in the compilation process of a method. It is relevant to profiling as it provides information about the reason for the compilation failure and the compilation identifier.

Fields:

  • failureMessage: A message indicating the reason for the compilation failure.
  • compileId: An identifier for the compilation process.

Profiling using this event:

  • The failureMessage field can be used to identify common reasons for compilation failures and investigate potential performance issues.
  • The compileId field can be used to associate the event with other events or data related to the compilation process.

Note

  • The event is triggered by the record_failure() method in the ciEnv class when a compilation failure occurs.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in c1_GraphBuilder.cpp, jvmciCompilerToVM.cpp, JFR.java, bytecodeInfo.cpp, compilerEvent.hpp, and compilerEvent.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CompilerInlining event in JFR is used for profiling the inlining decisions made by the compiler. It provides information about the inlining process and the decisions made by the compiler.

Relevance to profiling:

  • It helps in understanding how the compiler optimizes the code by inlining method calls.
  • It provides insights into the success or failure of the inlining process and the reasons behind it.
  • The compileId field identifies the compilation unit associated with the event, allowing for analysis of specific compilations.
  • The caller field contains information about the method that made the call.
  • The callee field contains information about the method that was called.
  • The succeeded field indicates whether the inlining was successful or not.
  • The message field provides additional information or context about the inlining decision.
  • The bci field represents the bytecode index where the inlining occurred. This can help in pinpointing the exact location in the code.

Using this event and its fields, one can analyze the impact of inlining decisions on the performance and optimize the code accordingly.

Deoptimization

default profiling startTime eventThread stackTrace 14 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Compiler

Describes the detection of an uncommon situation in a compiled method which may lead to deoptimization of the method

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in deoptimization.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The Deoptimization event in JFR represents the occurrence of deoptimization in the Java Virtual Machine (JVM). Here's what you need to know about this event for profiling:

  • The Deoptimization event has several fields that provide information about the deoptimization event:

    • compileId - The identifier of the compiled method.
    • compiler - The type of compiler used to compile the method.
    • method - The method being deoptimized.
    • lineNumber - The line number in the source code where the deoptimization occurred.
    • bci - The bytecode index where the deoptimization occurred.
    • instruction - The instruction being executed when the deoptimization occurred.
    • reason - The reason for the deoptimization.
    • action - The action taken as a result of the deoptimization.

  • The Deoptimization event is valuable for profiling because it provides insights into the situations where the JVM decides to deoptimize a compiled method and fall back to interpretation. It allows you to understand the reasons for deoptimization and the actions taken, which can help identify performance issues and optimize code accordingly.

  • By analyzing the Deoptimization event fields, you can identify which methods and bytecode instructions are more prone to deoptimization. This information can guide you in profiling and optimizing your code to minimize deoptimization occurrences and improve performance.

  • The Deoptimization event can be used in conjunction with other JFR events and profiling tools to gain a comprehensive understanding of the JVM's optimization and deoptimization behavior.

CompilerStatistics

default profiling startTime everychunk 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Compiler

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The CompilerStatistics event in JFR provides information about the compilation activity in the JVM. It is relevant for profiling purposes. The event includes the following fields:

  • compileCount: Number of compiled methods.
  • bailoutCount: Number of compilations that failed and reverted to interpreter.
  • invalidatedCount: Number of compilations that became invalidated due to class loading or other reasons.
  • osrCompileCount: Number of on-stack replacement (OSR) compilations.
  • standardCompileCount: Number of standard compilations.
  • osrBytesCompiled: Total number of bytes compiled using OSR.
  • standardBytesCompiled: Total number of bytes compiled using standard compilation.
  • nmethodsSize: Size of the compiled methods.
  • nmethodCodeSize: Size of the code generated by the compiled methods.
  • peakTimeSpent: Peak time spent on compilation.
  • totalTimeSpent: Total time spent on compilation.

By analyzing these fields, developers can gain insights into the performance and efficiency of the JVM's compilation process. For profiling purposes, they can monitor the number of compilations, identify areas with high bailout or invalidated counts, and optimize the compilation process accordingly. Additionally, the event provides information about the memory usage and code sizes of the compiled methods, allowing developers to optimize memory consumption and improve overall performance.

Configuration enabled period
default true 1000 ms
profiling true 1000 ms

Field Type Description
compileCount int Compiled Methods
bailoutCount int Bailouts
invalidatedCount int Invalidated Compilations
osrCompileCount int OSR Compilations
standardCompileCount int Standard Compilations
osrBytesCompiled ulong: bytes OSR Bytes Compiled
standardBytesCompiled ulong: bytes Standard Bytes Compiled
nmethodsSize ulong: bytes Compilation Resulting Size
nmethodCodeSize ulong: bytes Compilation Resulting Code Size
peakTimeSpent long: millis Peak Time
totalTimeSpent long: millis Total time

HeapDump

default profiling startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 15 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Diagnostics

Information about a successfully written Java heap dump

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in heapDumper.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The HeapDump event in JFR represents a heap dump operation, which captures the state of the Java heap at a specific point in time. It is used for profiling purposes to analyze memory usage and identify potential memory leaks.

The relevant fields of the HeapDump event are:

  • destination: The path where the heap dump is saved.
  • size: The size of the heap dump file in bytes.
  • gcBeforeDump: Indicates whether a garbage collection was performed before the heap dump was taken.
  • onOutOfMemoryError: Indicates whether the heap dump was triggered by an out-of-memory error.
  • overwrite: Specifies whether the heap dump should overwrite any existing file at the destination path.
  • compression: Specifies the level of gzip compression applied to the heap dump file (0 means no compression).

To use the HeapDump event for profiling, you can monitor its occurrence and examine the field values to analyze memory usage patterns and investigate memory-related issues.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default true true 0 ns
profiling true true 0 ns

Field Type Description
destination string Destination Path of the Dump
size long Size
gcBeforeDump boolean GC Before Dump
onOutOfMemoryError boolean Heap Dump on Out of Memory Error
overwrite boolean 21+ Overwrite Heap dump overwrites previous file location if it exists
compression int 21+ Compression Level Compression level of the dump, if larger than 0 we use gzip compression with this level

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Diagnostics

A Java programming language agent making use of the java.lang.instrument package for instrumenting programs running on the JVM

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JavaAgent event is used in Java Flight Recorder (JFR) for profiling purposes. It provides information about Java agents that are attached to the Java Virtual Machine (JVM). The relevance of this event is as follows:

  • name: The name of the Java agent.
  • options: The options used when attaching the Java agent to the JVM.
  • dynamic: Indicates whether the agent was attached dynamically during runtime or at JVM startup.
  • initializationTime: The time at which the JVM initialized the Java agent.
  • initializationDuration: The duration of the initialization method execution, which can be either premain or agentmain.

This event is useful for profiling purposes as it allows users to gather information about the Java agents attached to the JVM, including their names, options, and initialization details. By analyzing this information, users can better understand the impact of different agents on the JVM's performance and behavior.

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Diagnostics

A native programming language agent making use of the JVMTI interface used by development, profiling and monitoring tools

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The NativeAgent event in JFR is used for profiling and provides information about the native agents attached to the JVM. Here is a concise explanation of the event and its fields:

  • name: The name of the native agent
  • options: The options specified for the native agent
  • dynamic: Indicates if the native agent was dynamically attached to the JVM during runtime
  • initializationTime: The time at which the JVM initialized the native agent
  • initializationDuration: The duration of executing the JVMTI VMInit event callback, or the duration of executing the call to Agent_OnAttach for dynamically loaded agents
  • path: The path of the native agent library

This event is relevant for profiling as it allows you to collect information about the native agents attached to the JVM, their initialization details, and the options specified for them. It can help in identifying and analyzing the impact of native agents on the JVM's performance.

Configuration enabled period
default true endChunk
profiling true endChunk

Field Type Description
name string Name
options string Options
dynamic boolean Dynamic If the library attached to the JVM dynamically during runtime, i.e. not at startup
initializationTime Ticks Initialization Time The time the JVM initialized the agent
initializationDuration Tickspan Initialization Duration The duration of executing the JVMTI VMInit event callback. If no VMInit callback is specified, the duration is 0. For a dynamically loaded agent, it is the duration of executing the call to Agent_OnAttach.
path string Path The path of the library

The IntFlagChanged event in JFR represents a change in the value of an integer flag.

This event is relevant for profiling because it allows monitoring and analysis of changes to integer flag values during runtime.

The fields of the IntFlagChanged event are:

  • name: the name of the flag that was changed
  • oldValue: the previous value of the flag
  • newValue: the new value of the flag
  • origin: the origin of the flag change (e.g., whether it was set manually or by the JVM's ergonomics)

By tracking these events, developers and performance analysts can gain insights into how changes in integer flag values impact the performance and behavior of the JVM.

GarbageCollection

default profiling startTime duration eventThread 11 17 21 22 23 graal vm

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Collector

Garbage collection performed by the JVM

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in gcTraceSend.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The GarbageCollection event in JFR represents a garbage collection event during the execution of a Java program. It is relevant for profiling as it provides information about the garbage collector's activity and can be used to analyze the impact of garbage collection on the performance of the application.

The fields of the GarbageCollection event are:

  • gcId: The identifier of the current garbage collection.
  • name: The name of the garbage collector used.
  • cause: The reason for triggering the garbage collection.
  • sumOfPauses: The sum of all the pauses in Java execution during the garbage collection.
  • longestPause: The duration of the longest pause during the garbage collection.

By analyzing the GarbageCollection event, developers can gain insights into the impact of garbage collection on the application's performance and identify areas for optimization. They can also compare different garbage collectors or tune the garbage collection parameters to improve overall application performance.

Configuration enabled threshold
default true 0 ms
profiling true 0 ms

Field Type Description
gcId uint GC Identifier
name GCName Name The name of the Garbage Collector
cause GCCause Cause The reason for triggering this Garbage Collection
sumOfPauses Tickspan Sum of Pauses Sum of all the times in which Java execution was paused during the garbage collection
longestPause Tickspan Longest Pause Longest individual pause during the garbage collection

The SystemGC event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) represents a garbage collection initiated by the system. It has relevance to profiling and its fields because:

  • invokedConcurrent: Indicates whether the garbage collection was performed concurrently (in parallel with the application) or not.

Profiling Analysis:

  • The SystemGC event helps in understanding the impact and behavior of garbage collection on the application's performance.
  • By analyzing the event data, we can identify the frequency and duration of system-triggered garbage collections.
  • The invokedConcurrent field provides insights into the concurrency level of the garbage collection, which is crucial for identifying potential pauses or delays in application execution.

This information is valuable for performance tuning and optimization, allowing developers to identify and address areas where garbage collection is impacting the application's responsiveness. The SystemGC event provides a more comprehensive understanding of garbage collection behavior and aids in profiling and improving the application's overall performance.

The ParallelOldGarbageCollection event in JFR represents a garbage collection event in which the parallel old garbage collector is used. Here is a concise explanation of its meaning and relevance to profiling:

The YoungGarbageCollection event is used in Java Flight Recorder (JFR) to capture information about young garbage collections during profiling. It provides insights into the behavior and performance of garbage collection in the young generation (often called the Eden space) of the Java heap.

The fields of the YoungGarbageCollection event are:

  • gcId: Represents the identifier of the garbage collection event.
  • tenuringThreshold: Indicates the tenuring threshold, which is the age at which objects are promoted from the young generation to the old generation.

By analyzing the YoungGarbageCollection event, developers can gain valuable information about the frequency, duration, and efficiency of young garbage collections. This information can be used for profiling and optimizing garbage collection settings to improve the overall performance of the Java application.

GCConfiguration

default profiling startTime duration endchunk 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Configuration

The configuration of the garbage collector

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The GCConfiguration event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) provides information about the garbage collector configuration and settings, which is relevant for profiling Java applications. The event includes the following fields:

  • youngCollector: The garbage collector used for the young generation.
  • oldCollector: The garbage collector used for the old generation.
  • parallelGCThreads: Number of parallel threads used for garbage collection.
  • concurrentGCThreads: Number of concurrent threads used for garbage collection.
  • usesDynamicGCThreads: Indicates whether a dynamic number of GC threads are used.
  • isExplicitGCConcurrent: Indicates whether System.gc() is executed concurrently or not.
  • isExplicitGCDisabled: Indicates whether System.gc() will cause a garbage collection or not.
  • pauseTarget: Target for GC pauses.
  • gcTimeRatio: Target for the ratio of runtime vs garbage collection time.

This event can be used to analyze and profile the garbage collection behavior and performance of Java applications. The values of these fields help identify the garbage collector configuration and settings that affect the application's memory management and performance.

default true everyChunk
profiling true everyChunk

oldCollector GCName Old Garbage Collector The garbage collector used for the old generation
parallelGCThreads uint Parallel GC Threads Number of parallel threads to use for garbage collection
concurrentGCThreads uint Concurrent GC Threads Number of concurrent threads to use for garbage collection
usesDynamicGCThreads boolean Uses Dynamic GC Threads Whether a dynamic number of GC threads are used or not
isExplicitGCConcurrent boolean Concurrent Explicit GC Whether System.gc() is concurrent or not
isExplicitGCDisabled boolean Disabled Explicit GC Whether System.gc() will cause a garbage collection or not
pauseTarget long: millis Pause Target Target for GC pauses
gcTimeRatio uint GC Time Ratio Target for runtime vs garbage collection time

The GCTLABConfiguration event in JFR represents the configuration information related to Thread Local Allocation Buffers (TLABs). TLABs are used by the JVM to allocate memory for objects in the heap. This event provides the following information for profiling:

  • usesTLABs: Indicates whether TLABs are used or not. It can be used to determine the impact of TLABs on memory allocation.
  • minTLABSize: Specifies the minimum size of a TLAB. It can help determine the initial allocation size for TLABs.
  • tlabRefillWasteLimit: Represents the waste limit for TLAB refills. It can be used to identify the efficiency of TLAB allocation.

By monitoring the values of these fields in the GCTLABConfiguration event, developers can gain insights into the TLAB configuration and its impact on memory allocation performance.

GCHeapConfiguration

default profiling startTime duration endchunk 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Configuration

The configuration of the garbage collected heap

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The GCHeapConfiguration event in JFR provides information about the configuration of the garbage collector heap. It is relevant for profiling the memory management of an application. The event includes the following fields:

  • minSize: the minimum heap size
  • maxSize: the maximum heap size
  • initialSize: the initial heap size
  • usesCompressedOops: indicates whether compressed Oops (Ordinary Object Pointers) are enabled
  • compressedOopsMode: the type of compressed Oops being used
  • objectAlignment: the object alignment in bytes on the heap
  • heapAddressBits: the size of the heap address in bits

Profiling tools can use these fields to understand the heap configuration and optimize memory usage in the application.

Configuration enabled period
default true beginChunk
profiling true beginChunk

The G1MMU event in JFR is used for profiling and provides information about the memory management unit (MMU) behavior during garbage collection (GC) in the G1 garbage collector. It includes the following fields:

  • gcId: Identifies the current GC operation.
  • timeSlice: Represents the time slice used to calculate the MMU, which is the duration of a specific phase or iteration of the GC process.
  • gcTime: Indicates the amount of time stopped due to GC during the last time slice.
  • pauseTarget: Represents the maximum time allowed to be spent on GC during the last time slice.

This event helps in understanding the time distribution and efficiency of GC pauses. By analyzing the timeSlice, gcTime, and pauseTarget fields, developers can obtain insights into GC behavior and performance characteristics for optimizing memory management in applications.

The EvacuationInformation event in JFR provides information about the evacuation phase of a garbage collection (GC) in the G1 garbage collector. It is relevant for profiling the memory usage and performance of the GC. The event includes the following fields:

  • gcId: The identifier of the GC event.
  • cSetRegions: The number of regions in the collection set, which is the set of regions selected for garbage collection.
  • cSetUsedBefore: The memory usage in the collection set before the GC.
  • cSetUsedAfter: The memory usage in the collection set after the GC.
  • allocationRegions: The regions chosen as allocation regions during evacuation, including survivors and old space regions.
  • allocationRegionsUsedBefore: The memory usage in the allocation regions before the GC.
  • allocationRegionsUsedAfter: The memory usage in the allocation regions after the GC.
  • bytesCopied: The total number of bytes copied during the evacuation phase.
  • regionsFreed: The number of regions freed during the evacuation phase.

These fields provide insights into the memory utilization and efficiency of the evacuation process in the G1 garbage collector, which can help analyze the performance and identify potential areas for optimization.

G1BasicIHOP

default profiling startTime 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Detailed

Appearing in: G1GC

Missing in: ParallelGC, SerialGC, ShenandoahGC, ZGC

Basic statistics related to current IHOP calculation

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in g1Trace.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The G1BasicIHOP event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) is used to report basic statistics related to Incremental Heap Optimization (IHOP) in the Garbage First (G1) garbage collector. IHOP is a feature in G1 GC that improves mixed garbage collection pause times by incrementally adjusting the old generation occupancy before a mixed GC starts.

The G1BasicIHOP event provides the following fields for profiling and analysis:

  • gcId: Identifier for the garbage collection event
  • threshold: Current IHOP threshold value
  • thresholdPercentage: Current IHOP threshold value as a percentage of old generation occupancy
  • targetOccupancy: Target old generation occupancy to reach at the start of mixed GC
  • currentOccupancy: Current old generation occupancy
  • recentMutatorAllocationSize: Mutator allocation during the most recent interval
  • recentMutatorDuration: Duration of mutator operation in the most recent interval
  • recentAllocationRate: Allocation rate of the mutator in the most recent interval
  • lastMarkingDuration: Duration from the end of the last concurrent start to the first mixed GC

By analyzing the values of these fields, you can gain insights into the behavior and efficiency of the G1 GC and its IHOP mechanism. For example:

  • Monitoring the targetOccupancy and currentOccupancy fields can help determine if the G1 GC is effectively maintaining the desired old generation occupancy.
  • Analyzing the recentMutatorAllocationSize, recentMutatorDuration, and recentAllocationRate fields can provide information about the mutator's allocation behavior and its impact on garbage collection.
  • The lastMarkingDuration field can indicate how long the marking phase took in the most recent GC cycle.

Overall, the G1BasicIHOP event is a valuable tool for understanding and optimizing the performance of the G1 garbage collector in Java applications.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
gcId uint GC Identifier
threshold ulong: bytes Current IHOP Threshold Current IHOP threshold
thresholdPercentage float: percentage Current IHOP Threshold Current IHOP threshold in percent of old generation
targetOccupancy ulong: bytes Target Occupancy Target old generation occupancy to reach at the start of mixed GC
currentOccupancy ulong: bytes Current Occupancy Current old generation occupancy
recentMutatorAllocationSize ulong: bytes Recent Mutator Allocation Size Mutator allocation during mutator operation in the most recent interval
recentMutatorDuration long: millis Recent Mutator Duration Time the mutator ran in the most recent interval
recentAllocationRate double: bytes-per-second Recent Allocation Rate Allocation rate of the mutator in the most recent interval in bytes/second
lastMarkingDuration long: millis Last Marking Duration Last time from the end of the last concurrent start to the first mixed GC

PromoteObjectInNewPLAB

profiling startTime eventThread 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Detailed

Appearing in: G1GC, ParallelGC

Missing in: SerialGC, ShenandoahGC, ZGC

Object survived scavenge and was copied to a new Promotion Local Allocation Buffer (PLAB). Supported GCs are Parallel Scavenge, G1 and CMS with Parallel New. Due to promotion being done in parallel an object might be reported multiple times as the GC threads race to copy all objects.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in gcTraceSend.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The PromoteObjectInNewPLAB event in JFR represents the promotion of an object from a Young generation (Eden or Survivor space) to the Old generation, specifically when the promotion happens within a PLAB (Parallel Live Allocation Buffer). This event is relevant for profiling because it provides information about the promotion process during garbage collection, which can be useful for analyzing memory usage and tracing object lifetimes.

Meaning and relevance of the event:

  • gcId: Identifier signifying the garbage collection during which the object was promoted
  • objectClass: Class of the promoted object
  • objectSize: Size of the promoted object
  • tenuringAge: Tenuring age of the surviving object before being copied to the Old generation. It represents the number of scavenges the object has survived.
  • tenured: Indicates whether the object was promoted to the Old generation. If false, it means the object was aged and copied to a Survivor space.
  • plabSize: Size of the allocated Parallel Live Allocation Buffer (PLAB) to which the object was copied

Usage for profiling:

  • Monitor the frequency and size of object promotions from Young to Old generation
  • Analyze the distribution of promoted objects by class and size
  • Identify objects with high tenuring ages, which may indicate long-lived objects or suboptimal garbage collection strategies
  • Evaluate the efficiency of PLAB sizing by examining the size of PLABs used for promotions

Configuration enabled
default false
profiling true

Field Type Description
gcId uint GC Identifier Identifier signifying GC during which the object was promoted
objectClass Class Object Class Class of promoted object
objectSize ulong: bytes Object Size Size of promoted object
tenuringAge uint Object Tenuring Age Tenuring age of a surviving object before being copied. The tenuring age of an object is a value between 0-15 and is incremented each scavenge the object survives. Newly allocated objects have tenuring age 0.
tenured boolean Tenured True if object was promoted to Old space, otherwise the object was aged and copied to a Survivor space
plabSize ulong: bytes PLAB Size Size of the allocated PLAB to which the object was copied

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in gcTraceSend.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

  • The PromotionFailed event is used to track failed object promotions during garbage collection in the Java Flight Recorder (JFR) profiling tool.
  • This event is important for profiling because it provides information about objects that were not successfully promoted from the young generation to the old generation during garbage collection.
  • The promotionFailed field in the event contains data about the failed promotion, such as the number of failed objects, the size of the first failed object, the smallest failed object size, and the total size of all failed objects.
  • The gcId field indicates the identifier of the garbage collection event associated with the promotion failure.
  • The thread field indicates the running thread at the time of the promotion failure.
  • By analyzing the PromotionFailed events, developers or profilers can identify potential performance issues or objects that might be causing memory pressure in the application.

Profiling information provided by the GCCPUTime event helps in analyzing the CPU utilization and efficiency of garbage collection. It can be used to identify performance bottlenecks and optimize the garbage collection process.

The TenuringDistribution event in JFR represents the distribution of objects according to their age during garbage collection. It is relevant for profiling as it provides information on how objects are being tenured or promoted to older generations.

In the given code, the send_tenuring_distribution_event method is responsible for creating and sending a TenuringDistribution event with the provided age and size parameters. It checks if the event should be committed and sets the corresponding fields before committing it.

The is_tenuring_distribution_event_enabled method is used to check if the TenuringDistribution event is enabled or not.

  • gcId: Represents the identifier of the garbage collection.
  • age: Indicates the age of the objects being tenured or promoted.
  • size: Represents the size of the objects being tenured or promoted.

The G1HeapRegionTypeChange event is used for profiling in Java Flight Recorder (JFR). It indicates a change in the type of a heap region in the Garbage First (G1) garbage collector.

This event has the following relevant fields:

  • index: The index of the heap region that changed type.
  • from: The previous type of the heap region.
  • to: The new type of the heap region.
  • start: The starting address of the heap region.

By examining the G1HeapRegionTypeChange events, the profiler can obtain information about the changes in region types and their memory usage. This can help in analyzing and optimizing the garbage collection process in applications using the G1 garbage collector.

ObjectCount

startTime everychunk 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Detailed

Appearing in: G1GC, ParallelGC, SerialGC

Missing in: ShenandoahGC, ZGC

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in objectCountEventSender.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ObjectCount event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) is used for profiling and provides information about the count and size of objects in memory after garbage collection. The event has the following fields:

  • gcId: This field represents the identifier of the garbage collection event.
  • objectClass: It denotes the class of the objects being profiled.
  • count: This field indicates the number of objects of the given class.
  • totalSize: It signifies the total size in bytes occupied by the objects.

To use this event for profiling, the following steps can be followed:

  1. Enable the ObjectCount event using the enable_requestable_event() method in the ObjectCountEventSender class.
  2. Call the send() method in the ObjectCountEventSender class, providing the necessary parameters such as the class, count, and size of the objects being profiled.
  3. If the event should be sent, create a new instance of the event (EventObjectCount or EventObjectCountAfterGC), set the relevant fields (like starttime, endtime, gcId, objectClass, count, and totalSize), and commit the event to JFR using the commit() method.

By using the ObjectCount event and its fields, developers can gather valuable information about object counts and sizes in order to analyze memory usage and identify potential memory leaks or performance issues in their applications.

The ZPageAllocation event in JFR represents the allocation of a ZPage in the Z garbage collector. It provides information about the allocation request, such as the type and size of the page. This event is relevant for profiling because it allows monitoring and analysis of page allocations in the Z garbage collector.

The fields of the ZPageAllocation event are:

  • type: the type of the ZPage
  • size: the size of the ZPage
  • flushed: the number of pages flushed during the allocation process
  • committed: the number of pages successfully committed
  • segments: the number of memory segments in the page
  • nonBlocking: a flag indicating if the allocation was non-blocking

By analyzing the ZPageAllocation events, you can gain insights into the allocation patterns and efficiency of the Z garbage collector. It helps understand memory utilization, flush rates, and success rates of page allocations. This information can be used to optimize the garbage collector's performance and memory management strategies.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in xTracer.inline.hpp, xTracer.cpp, zTracer.inline.hpp, and zTracer.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ZThreadPhase event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) represents a phase of execution within a thread during garbage collection. It is used for profiling purposes.

Fields of the ZThreadPhase event include:

  • gcId: An identifier for the garbage collection
  • name: The name of the phase

Key points about the ZThreadPhase event:

  • It is designed specifically for profiling garbage collection in Java applications.
  • It provides information about the phases of execution within a thread during garbage collection.
  • The gcId field helps identify the specific garbage collection event associated with this thread phase.
  • The name field represents the name or description of the phase.
  • The event is marked as experimental, indicating that it is still in development and subject to potential changes in future versions of JFR.

You can use the ZThreadPhase event to profile and analyze the execution phases of threads during garbage collection, allowing you to gain insights into the performance and behavior of your application.

ZUncommit

default profiling startTime duration eventThread 15 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Detailed

Uncommitting of memory

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in xUncommitter.cpp, and zUncommitter.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ZUncommit event in JFR is used for profiling and monitoring the uncommitted memory in the Z Garbage Collector.

  • The uncommitted field of the event represents the amount of memory that was uncommitted during the profiling session.

To use the event for profiling:

  1. The ZUncommitter class has a run_thread method that listens for the ZUncommit event.
  2. Inside the run_thread method, the amount of memory uncommitted is tracked.
  3. After uncommitting memory, the statistics are updated using the ZCounterUncommit field.
  4. The event is then sent with the amount of memory uncommitted.

By monitoring the ZUncommit event, it is possible to profile and analyze the uncommitted memory in the Z Garbage Collector to optimize memory usage and performance.

Configuration enabled threshold
default true 0 ms
profiling true 0 ms

Field Type Description
uncommitted ulong: bytes Uncommitted

The ZUnmap event in JFR is used for profiling and monitoring memory unmapping and destruction in the Z Garbage Collector (GC). It provides information about when and how much memory is unmapped and destroyed during the garbage collection process.

Relevance of the event to profiling and its fields:

  • unmapped: Represents the amount of memory that has been unmapped and destroyed.
  • By monitoring the ZUnmap event, profiling tools can analyze the memory unmapping behavior of the Z GC, identify any synchronous unmapping, and detect if the unmapper thread is lagging behind due to asynchronous unmapping being unable to keep up with the pace.

The ShenandoahHeapRegionStateChange event in JFR represents a change in the state of a Shenandoah heap region. This event is relevant for profiling purposes, as it provides information about the change in state and the corresponding fields.

Fields of the ShenandoahHeapRegionStateChange event:

  • index: The index of the heap region.
  • from: The previous state of the heap region.
  • to: The new state of the heap region.
  • start: The memory address where the heap region starts.
  • used: The amount of memory used in the heap region.

This event can be used to track and analyze changes in the state of Shenandoah heap regions during profiling. By examining the from and to states, it is possible to gain insights into how memory is allocated and deallocated in the heap regions.

GCLocker

default profiling startTime eventThread stackTrace 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Detailed

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in gcTraceSend.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The GCLocker event in JFR represents the behavior of the GC locker during garbage collection. It provides information about the number of Java threads that are in a critical section when the GC locker is started (lockCount) and the number of threads that are stalled by the GC locker (stallCount).

This event is relevant for profiling as it allows developers to analyze the impact of the GC locker on the execution of Java threads during garbage collection. The lockCount field helps identify the threads that are potentially causing contention issues, while the stallCount field indicates the number of threads that are delayed due to the GC locker. By monitoring and analyzing these fields, developers can optimize the performance of their applications by reducing the impact of the GC locker on concurrent execution.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default true true 1 s
profiling true true 100 ms

Field Type Description
lockCount uint Lock Count The number of Java threads in a critical section when the GC locker is started
stallCount uint Stall Count The number of Java threads stalled by the GC locker

This event can be used to track the memory usage of the Java application and analyze garbage collection performance. By monitoring the heapUsed field, developers can identify memory leaks, inefficient memory allocation, and fragmentation issues.

MetaspaceSummary

default profiling startTime 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Heap

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in gcTraceSend.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The MetaspaceSummary event in JFR provides profiling information about the metaspace memory usage during garbage collection.

Relevance to profiling:

  • It contains the gcId field, which identifies the specific garbage collection event.
  • The when field indicates when the event occurred during the garbage collection.
  • The gcThreshold field represents the threshold value for garbage collection.
  • The metaspace field provides information about the total metaspace, including both class and non-class space.
  • The dataSpace field specifically captures memory usage in the data space (non-class space).
  • The classSpace field captures memory usage in the class space.

Profiling Usage:

  • By analyzing the values of these fields, we can understand how the metaspace memory is used during garbage collection.
  • It helps in identifying memory utilization patterns and potential bottlenecks in the metaspace.
  • By tracking changes in memory usage over multiple garbage collections, we can identify trends and take necessary optimization measures.
  • This event can be used in conjunction with other JFR events to gain a comprehensive understanding of the JVM's behavior and memory usage.

profiling true

PSHeapSummary

default profiling startTime 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / GC / Heap

Appearing in: ParallelGC

Missing in: G1GC, SerialGC, ShenandoahGC, ZGC

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in gcTraceSend.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The PSHeapSummary event in JFR provides a summary of the different memory spaces in the garbage collector's heap. It is relevant for profiling memory allocation and usage during garbage collection.

Fields:

  • gcId: Identifier of the garbage collection event
  • when: When the event occurred
  • oldSpace: Summary of the Old Space (memory region for long-lived objects)
  • oldObjectSpace: Summary of the Old Object Space (memory region for objects in the Old Space)
  • youngSpace: Summary of the Young Space (memory region for short-lived objects)
  • edenSpace: Summary of the Eden Space (memory region for newly allocated objects)
  • fromSpace: Summary of the From Space (memory region for objects being moved during garbage collection)
  • toSpace: Summary of the To Space (memory region for objects being copied during garbage collection)

The PSHeapSummary event is useful for understanding memory usage patterns and optimizing garbage collection performance. It provides insights into the sizes and usage of different memory spaces during garbage collection, which can help in identifying memory leaks, inefficient memory allocation, or fragmented memory regions.

Configuration enabled
default true
profiling true

Field Type Description
gcId uint GC Identifier
when GCWhen When Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
oldSpace VirtualSpace struct Old Space Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
oldObjectSpace ObjectSpace struct Old Object Space Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
youngSpace VirtualSpace struct Young Space Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
edenSpace ObjectSpace struct Eden Space Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
fromSpace ObjectSpace struct From Space Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
toSpace ObjectSpace struct To Space Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.

The MetaspaceOOM event in JFR is used to report Out-of-Memory errors related to metaspace allocation failures. It contains the following fields:

  • classLoader: The class loader associated with the allocation failure.
  • hiddenClassLoader: Indicates whether the class loader has a hidden class mirror holder.
  • size: The size of the allocation failure in bytes.
  • metadataType: The type of metadata associated with the allocation failure.
  • metaspaceObjectType: The type of metaspace object associated with the allocation failure.

This event can be used for profiling by capturing information about metaspace allocation failures and understanding their causes. By analyzing the event data, developers can identify potential issues with metaspace usage and optimize memory allocation to prevent out-of-memory errors.

The MetaspaceChunkFreeListSummary event in JFR provides information about the usage of chunk free lists in the Metaspace area of memory. It is relevant for profiling as it allows us to monitor and analyze the memory usage patterns in the Metaspace.

The fields of the MetaspaceChunkFreeListSummary event are:

  • gcId: The identifier of the garbage collection event.
  • when: The point at which the event occurred.
  • metadataType: The type of metadata stored in the chunk.
  • specializedChunks: The number of specialized chunks in the free list.
  • specializedChunksTotalSize: The total size of specialized chunks in the free list.
  • smallChunks: The number of small chunks in the free list.
  • smallChunksTotalSize: The total size of small chunks in the free list.
  • mediumChunks: The number of medium chunks in the free list.
  • mediumChunksTotalSize: The total size of medium chunks in the free list.
  • humongousChunks: The number of humongous chunks in the free list.
  • humongousChunksTotalSize: The total size of humongous chunks in the free list.

By analyzing the values of these fields, we can gain insights into the distribution and utilization of different types of chunks in the Metaspace. This information can help identify potential memory fragmentation issues and optimize memory allocation strategies.

Overall, the GCPhasePauseLevel4 event is relevant for profiling garbage collection pauses and obtaining information about the specific pause phase being executed.

The InstantEvent is an event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) that represents an event that is not considered to have taken any time. It is used for profiling purposes.

Relevance to profiling and its fields:

  • commit(): Commits the event, indicating that it occurred.
  • shouldWrite(): Determines if the event would be written to the data stream if commit() is called. It depends on whether the event is enabled and other factors.

Overall, the InstantEvent is used to represent instantaneous events that do not consume any time and can be useful for profiling and analyzing performance in Java applications.

The ResidentSetSize event in JFR provides information about the memory usage of a process. It is relevant to profiling because it allows developers to monitor and analyze the memory consumption of their application.

The event has two fields:

  • size: Represents the current resident set size of the process, which indicates the amount of memory actively being used by the process.
  • peak: Represents the peak resident set size of the process, which indicates the maximum amount of memory the process has used at any point in time.

By monitoring this event, developers can identify memory-intensive sections of their application and optimize memory usage to improve performance and resource allocation.

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Profiling

A potential memory leak

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in eventEmitter.cpp, objectSampler.cpp, and jfrJniMethod.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The OldObjectSample event in JFR represents an object that has been sampled as part of old object profiling. It captures information about the object's allocation time, size, age, last known heap usage, GC root, and whether it is an array and the number of elements in the array.

This event is relevant for profiling as it allows developers to analyze the memory usage of long-lived objects in the application. By examining the fields of this event, one can gain insights into the memory allocation patterns, object longevity, and potential memory leaks in the application. By tracking the allocation time, size, and age of objects, developers can identify problematic objects that consume excessive memory or remain alive for an extended period. Additionally, information about the last known heap usage provides context about the object's memory usage. The arrayElements field helps determine if the object is an array and provides the number of elements in the array.

Overall, by leveraging the OldObjectSample event, developers can perform comprehensive memory profiling and optimize memory usage in their applications.

Snapshot of a threads state

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrJniMethod.cpp, and jfrThreadSampler.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ExecutionSample event in JFR provides information about a sampled execution point in an application. This event is relevant for profiling purposes.

Meaning and relevance of fields:

  • sampledThread: Represents the thread that was sampled.
  • stackTrace: Contains the stack trace information of the sampled thread.
  • state: Represents the state of the thread at the time of sampling.

This event can be used to gather profiling data and analyze the execution flow of threads in the application. By examining the stack trace and thread state, developers can identify performance bottlenecks, optimize code, and improve the overall efficiency of the application.

Auto generated description experimental

The NativeMethodSample event in JFR represents a sample of a native method call in a thread. It is relevant to profiling because it provides information about the execution of native methods in an application.

Fields:

  • sampledThread: Represents the thread in which the native method was sampled.
  • stackTrace: Represents the stack trace of the native method call.
  • state: Represents the state of the thread at the time of the sample.

This event can be used to analyze the performance and behavior of native methods in an application, allowing developers to identify potential bottlenecks and optimize their code. By examining the stack trace and thread state, it becomes possible to understand the context in which the native method was executed and make informed decisions for performance improvements.

ContinuationFreeze

experimental startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 19 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Runtime

Invocation of Continuation.yield()

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in continuationFreezeThaw.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ContinuationFreeze event in JFR represents the freezing of a continuation. It is relevant to profiling as it provides information about the freezing process and its impact on the stack. Some key points to understand about this event are:

  • carrierThread: The thread enlisted as a carrier for the frozen continuation.
  • continuationClass: The class associated with the continuation being frozen.
  • interpretedFrames: The number of interpreted frames present in the frozen continuation.
  • size: The stack size of the frozen continuation.

By analyzing the ContinuationFreeze event, profiling tools can gain insights into the freezing behavior of continuations and understand the impact on stack usage. This information can be used to optimize the freezing process and improve the performance of applications that heavily rely on continuations.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default false false 0 ms
profiling false false 0 ms

Field Type Description
carrierThread Thread Carrier Thread Thread enlisted as a carrier
continuationClass Class Continuation Class Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
interpretedFrames ushort Interpreted Frames
size ushort: bytes Stack Size

  • The event ContinuationThaw is experimental and related to continuation-based programming in Java.
  • It provides information about the carrier thread and continuation class involved in the thawing process.
  • It also includes details about the interpreted frames and the size of the stack.
  • This event can be used for profiling and analyzing the performance of continuation-based applications.

  • ContinuationFreezeFast is an experimental event in the Java Flight Recorder (JFR) framework.

  • The event has three fields:
    • id: Represents the ID of the continuation being frozen.
    • size: Indicates the size of the frozen stack chunk in bytes.
    • allocate: Indicates whether the frozen chunk was newly allocated.
  • The ContinuationFreezeFast event is useful for profiling and understanding the memory footprint and behavior of continuations in a Java application.

The SafepointBegin event can be used to track and analyze the safepoint operations in order to optimize and improve the performance of the application.
