The SafepointStateSynchronization event in JFR provides information about the state synchronization process during a safepoint in Java applications. It is relevant to profiling as it helps in understanding the behavior and performance of threads during a safepoint.

Fields of the SafepointStateSynchronization event:

  • safepointId: Identifier of the safepoint
  • initialThreadCount: The number of threads running at the beginning of the state check
  • runningThreadCount: The number of threads still running after the state check
  • iterations: Number of iterations performed during the state check

By analyzing these fields, one can gain insights into the impact of the safepoint on thread execution and overall application performance.

ExecuteVMOperation

default profiling startTime duration eventThread 11 17 21 22 23 graal vm

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Runtime

Execution of a VM Operation

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in vmThread.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ExecuteVMOperation event in JFR represents the execution of a VM operation in the JVM. It is relevant for profiling as it provides information about various fields related to the execution of the operation. The event has the following fields:

  • operation: Indicates the type of VM operation that was executed.
  • safepoint: Indicates whether the operation occurred at a safepoint (At Safepoint).
  • blocking: Indicates whether the calling thread was blocked until the operation was complete (Caller Blocked).
  • caller: Represents the thread that requested the operation. If the operation was non-blocking, the value will be 0 indicating that the thread is unknown (Caller).
  • safepointId: Represents the identifier of the safepoint under which the operation was completed. If the operation was not executed at a safepoint, the value will be 0 (Safepoint Identifier).

By analyzing the ExecuteVMOperation event and its fields, the profiler can gain insights into the execution of VM operations and understand the impact on the overall JVM performance.

Configuration enabled threshold
default true 10 ms
profiling true 0 ms

Field Type Description
operation VMOperationType Operation Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
safepoint boolean At Safepoint If the operation occurred at a safepoint
blocking boolean Caller Blocked If the calling thread was blocked until the operation was complete
caller Thread Caller Thread requesting operation. If non-blocking, will be set to 0 indicating thread is unknown
safepointId ulong Safepoint Identifier The safepoint (if any) under which this operation was completed

SymbolTableStatistics

default profiling startTime duration everychunk 13 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Virtual Machine / Runtime / Tables

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The SymbolTableStatistics event in JFR provides information and statistics about the symbol table, which is used to store interned strings in the JVM. This event is relevant for profiling and can be used to monitor the memory usage and performance of the symbol table. It includes the following fields:

  • bucketCount: The number of buckets in the symbol table.
  • entryCount: The total number of entries in the symbol table.
  • totalFootprint: The total memory footprint of the symbol table and its entries.
  • bucketCountMaximum: The maximum number of entries in a single bucket.
  • bucketCountAverage: The average number of entries in each bucket.
  • bucketCountVariance: The variance of the bucket sizes, indicating how spread out they are from the average.
  • bucketCountStandardDeviation: The standard deviation of the bucket sizes, indicating how far they are from the expected value.
  • insertionRate: The rate at which items are being added to the symbol table, measured in items per second.
  • removalRate: The rate at which items are being removed from the symbol table, measured in items per second.

By monitoring these statistics, developers can gain insights into the memory usage and performance characteristics of the symbol table, allowing them to optimize string internment and improve overall application performance.

Configuration enabled period
default true 10 s
profiling true 10 s

Field Type Description
bucketCount ulong Bucket Count Number of buckets
entryCount ulong Entry Count Number of all entries
totalFootprint ulong: bytes Total Footprint Total memory footprint (the table itself plus all of the entries)
bucketCountMaximum ulong Maximum Bucket Count The maximum bucket length (entries in a single bucket)
bucketCountAverage float Average Bucket Count The average bucket length
bucketCountVariance float Bucket Count Variance How far bucket lengths are spread out from their average value
bucketCountStandardDeviation float Bucket Count Standard Deviation How far bucket lengths are spread out from their mean (expected) value
insertionRate float Insertion Rate How many items were added since last event (per second)
removalRate float Removal Rate How many items were removed since last event (per second)

The StringTableStatistics event in JFR provides information about the statistics of the string table used in the JVM. It includes the following fields:

  • bucketCount: Number of buckets in the string table.
  • entryCount: Number of entries in the string table.
  • totalFootprint: Total memory footprint of the string table and all its entries.
  • bucketCountMaximum: The maximum number of entries in a single bucket.
  • bucketCountAverage: The average number of entries in each bucket.

  • bucketCountStandardDeviation: Standard deviation of the number of entries in the buckets.
  • insertionRate: Rate at which new items are added to the string table per second.
  • removalRate: Rate at which items are removed from the string table per second.

These statistics can be used for profiling the memory usage and performance of the string table in the JVM.

The ThreadDump event in JFR is used to capture a snapshot of all threads in the Java application at a specific moment. This event is relevant to profiling because it provides valuable information about the state of each thread, such as the stack trace, the thread's status, and any locks it holds.

The fields of the ThreadDump event are:

  • result: This field stores the thread dump information captured by the event. It contains the stack trace and other details of each thread in the application.

By analyzing the ThreadDump event, profiling tools can gain insights into thread behavior, identify threads that may be blocked or consuming excessive CPU time, and diagnose performance issues related to thread synchronization or contention.

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrThreadLocal.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JFR event ThreadStart is used for profiling in Java Flight Recorder (JFR). Here is a concise explanation of the event and its relevance to profiling:

  • The ThreadStart event in JFR is triggered when a new Java thread is started.
  • The event has two fields:
    • thread: Represents the newly created Java thread.
    • parentThread: Represents the parent Java thread that started the new thread.
  • This event is relevant to profiling as it allows you to track the creation of new threads and their hierarchy.
  • By analyzing the ThreadStart events, you can understand the thread creation patterns and identify any bottlenecks or inefficiencies in your application's thread management.
  • This information can be used to optimize your application's performance and make better decisions regarding thread handling and resource allocation.

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrThreadLocal.cpp, and java.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ThreadEnd event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) signifies the end of a Java thread's execution. It is relevant to profiling and offers valuable information for analyzing application performance. Here is a concise explanation of the event:

  • The ThreadEnd event represents the termination of a Java thread.
  • The event has a single field, thread, which represents the Java thread that has ended.
  • It is useful for profiling purposes as it allows profiling tools to collect data on the execution behavior of threads.
  • By analyzing ThreadEnd events, one can gain insights into thread utilization, thread lifecycles, and potential bottlenecks in multi-threaded applications.
  • The event helps in identifying threads that may have ended unexpectedly or threads that have completed their tasks efficiently.
  • Profiling tools can use this event to track the overall thread execution time, resource utilization, and thread interactions within an application.
  • It is an essential event for profiling and optimization tasks, providing critical information about the behavior of Java threads.

ThreadPark

default profiling startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23 graal vm

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in unsafe.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ThreadPark event in JFR represents a thread being parked or put to sleep. It is relevant to profiling as it provides information about the thread and its park operation.

The event contains the following fields:

  • parkedClass: The class on which the thread is parked.
  • timeout: The timeout value for the park operation.
  • until: The absolute time until which the thread is parked.
  • address: The address of the object on which the thread is parked.

This event can be used to profile the behavior of threads being parked and the duration of their park operations.

JavaMonitorEnter

default profiling startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23 graal vm

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in objectMonitor.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JavaMonitorEnter event in JFR represents the act of a Java thread attempting to enter a monitor (a lock) on an object.

Relevance to profiling:

  • This event is relevant for profiling as it provides information about contention for locks and potential performance bottlenecks in multi-threaded applications.
  • It can help identify which monitor is being entered and which thread from the previous owner relinquishes it.
  • The previousOwner field indicates the previous owner of the monitor, which can be used to analyze lock contention patterns.
  • The monitorClass field indicates the class of the object on which the monitor is acquired.

Fields:

  • monitorClass: Class of the object being monitored.
  • previousOwner: Thread ID of the previous owner of the monitor.
  • address: Address of the monitor, which provides a unique identifier for the monitor events.

Overall, the JavaMonitorEnter event in JFR is useful for profiling multi-threaded applications and analyzing the behavior of thread synchronization through monitor acquisition.

JavaMonitorWait

default profiling startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23 graal vm

Category: Java Application

Waiting on a Java monitor

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in objectMonitor.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JavaMonitorWait event in JFR represents a thread waiting on a monitor lock. It is relevant for profiling as it provides information about the occurrence and characteristics of monitor waits.

  • monitorClass: The class of the object that is being waited on.
  • notifier: The thread that will notify the waiting thread when the lock is released.
  • timeout: The maximum amount of time the waiting thread will wait for the lock to be released.
  • timedOut: Indicates if the wait has timed out.
  • address: The address of the monitor lock.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default true true 20 ms
profiling true true 10 ms

monitorClass Class Monitor Class Class of object waited on
notifier Thread Notifier Thread Notifying Thread
timeout long: millis Timeout Maximum wait time
timedOut boolean Timed Out Wait has been timed out
address ulong: address Monitor Address Address of object waited on

JavaMonitorInflate

profiling startTime duration eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23 graal vm

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in synchronizer.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JavaMonitorInflate event in JFR represents the inflation of a monitor object in Java.

This event is relevant to profiling as it allows developers to track and analyze the causes and frequency of monitor inflation in their application.

The fields of the JavaMonitorInflate event are:

  • monitorClass: the class of the monitor object that was inflated
  • address: the address of the inflated monitor object
  • cause: the cause of the inflation, indicating why the monitor was inflated

By examining the monitorClass, address, and cause fields of this event, developers can identify which monitors are being inflated, understand the reasons behind the inflation, and optimize their code or system to reduce monitor inflation and improve performance.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default false true 20 ms
profiling true true 10 ms

Field Type Description
monitorClass Class Monitor Class Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
address ulong: address Monitor Address
cause InflateCause Monitor Inflation Cause Cause of inflation

Allocation in new Thread Local Allocation Buffer

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in allocTracer.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ObjectAllocationInNewTLAB event in JFR is relevant for profiling purposes in Java.

This event captures information about object allocations that occur within a Thread Local Allocation Buffer (TLAB) in the Java Virtual Machine (JVM).

The event has the following fields:

  • objectClass: Represents the class of the allocated object.
  • allocationSize: Specifies the size of the allocation.
  • tlabSize: Indicates the size of the TLAB.

By analyzing these events, developers can gain insights into the object allocation patterns and sizes within TLABs, which can help optimize memory usage and identify potential issues. It provides valuable information for profiling and performance analysis.

ObjectAllocationOutsideTLAB

startTime eventThread stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Application

Allocation outside Thread Local Allocation Buffers

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in allocTracer.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ObjectAllocationOutsideTLAB event in JFR is relevant for profiling and monitoring the allocation of objects that occur outside of a Thread Local Allocation Buffer (TLAB) in the Java Virtual Machine (JVM). This event is important for understanding memory allocation patterns and potential performance bottlenecks in an application.

The event has two fields:

  • objectClass (Object Class): Represents the class of the allocated object.
  • allocationSize (Allocation Size): Indicates the size of the allocation.

By capturing instances of this event, developers and performance analysts can gain insights into the frequency, distribution, and characteristics of object allocations that bypassed the TLAB mechanism.

To use this event for profiling purposes, the should_commit() method should be invoked to determine if the event should be recorded or not. If it should be recorded, the objectClass and allocationSize fields should be set accordingly before invoking the commit() method to publish the event.

By analyzing the data collected from this event, developers can identify memory usage patterns, understand the impact of object allocations outside of TLABs on garbage collection, and optimize memory allocation strategies to improve performance.

default false true
profiling false true

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrObjectAllocationSample.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ObjectAllocationSample event in JFR is used for profiling object allocation in Java applications. It provides information about the class of the allocated object and the relative weight of the sample.

  • objectClass: Represents the class of the allocated object.
  • weight: Indicates the relative weight of the sample. It helps to understand the allocation pressure by aggregating the weights of a large number of samples for a specific class, thread, or stack trace.

FileForce

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/FileForceEvent.java

Category: Java Application

Force updates to be written to file

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in FileForceEvent.java, EventConfigurations.java, JDKEvents.java, and FileChannelImplInstrumentor.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The FileForceEvent in JFR is an event that represents forcing updates to be written to a file. It is relevant to profiling as it allows you to gather information about file force operations in your Java application.

This event has the following fields:

  • path: Represents the full path of the file being forced to update (String).
  • metaData: Indicates whether the file metadata is updated during the force operation (boolean).

To use this event for profiling, you can:

  • Enable the FileForceEvent event configuration (EventConfigurations.FILE_FORCE) to start collecting data.
  • Use the commit method of FileForceEvent to record an event instance when a file force operation occurs, passing the corresponding values for start (the start timestamp), duration (the duration of the operation), path, and metaData.

By analyzing the collected FileForceEvent instances, you can gain insights into the frequency, duration, and other details of file force operations in your application, aiding in performance optimization and debugging.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default true true 20 ms
profiling true true 10 ms

Field Type Description
path string Path Full path of the file
metaData boolean Update Metadata Whether the file metadata is updated

SocketWrite

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/SocketWriteEvent.java

Category: Java Application

Writing data to a socket

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in SocketWriteEvent.java, EventConfigurations.java, JDKEvents.java, SocketChannelImplInstrumentor.java, and SocketOutputStreamInstrumentor.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The SocketWrite event in JFR represents writing data to a socket in a Java application. It provides information about the remote host, address, port, and the number of bytes written to the socket.

This event is relevant for profiling as it allows developers to measure the performance and efficiency of socket write operations in their application.

Fields of the SocketWrite event:

  • host: the remote host where the socket connection is established
  • address: the remote address of the socket
  • port: the remote port of the socket
  • bytesWritten: the number of bytes written to the socket

By analyzing the data provided by this event, developers can identify potential bottlenecks, optimize network communication, and improve the overall efficiency of their application.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default true true 20 ms
profiling true true 10 ms

Field Type Description
host string Remote Host
address string Remote Address
port int Remote Port
bytesWritten long: bytes Bytes Written Number of bytes written to the socket

Writing data to a file

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in EventConfigurations.java, FileWriteEvent.java, JDKEvents.java, RandomAccessFileInstrumentor.java, FileChannelImplInstrumentor.java, and FileOutputStreamInstrumentor.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The FileWrite event in JFR represents the action of writing data to a file in a Java application. It is relevant for profiling to track file write operations and their impact on performance. The event has two fields:

  • path: Represents the full path of the file being written, or "N/A" if a file descriptor was used to create the stream.
  • bytesWritten: Indicates the number of bytes written to the file.

By capturing instances of the FileWrite event during execution, developers can analyze the frequency, duration, and patterns of file write operations, allowing them to optimize code and identify potential performance bottlenecks related to file I/O.

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in VirtualThreadEndEvent.java, JDKEvents.java, VirtualThread.java, and VirtualThreadEndEvent.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The VirtualThreadEnd event is a Java Flight Recorder (JFR) event that captures the termination of a virtual thread. Here's some important information about this event:

  • The VirtualThreadEnd event is categorized under "Java Application" and labeled as "Virtual Thread End".
  • The event class is jdk.jfr.events.VirtualThreadEndEvent.
  • It extends the AbstractJDKEvent class.
  • The event has one field:
    • javaThreadId (labeled as "Thread Id"): Represents the thread ID of the virtual thread that has ended.

Relevance to profiling:

  • The VirtualThreadEnd event is useful for profiling and monitoring application performance.
  • It provides information about virtual threads that have finished executing, allowing for analysis of thread behavior and resource utilization.
  • By tracking the termination of virtual threads, you can gain insights into how threads are being utilized and identify any potential bottlenecks or performance issues.
  • Profiling tools can leverage this event to collect data on virtual thread termination and analyze thread usage patterns.
  • The VirtualThreadEnd event can be enabled in JFR to capture data during profiling sessions and performance testing.

Configuration enabled
default false
profiling false

Field Type Description
javaThreadId long Thread Id

SocketRead

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 11 17 21 22 23

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/SocketReadEvent.java

Category: Java Application

Reading data from a socket

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in SocketReadEvent.java, EventConfigurations.java, JDKEvents.java, SocketChannelImplInstrumentor.java, and SocketInputStreamInstrumentor.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The SocketRead event is used to track the process of reading data from a socket in a Java application. It is relevant for profiling to gain insights into the socket read operations and analyze their performance. The fields of the SocketRead event provide important information about the reading process. These fields include:

  • host: The remote host from which the data is being read.
  • address: The remote address of the host.
  • port: The remote port on which the host is listening.
  • timeout: The timeout value for the socket read operation, measured in milliseconds.
  • bytesRead: The number of bytes successfully read from the socket.
  • endOfStream: A boolean value indicating whether the end of the data stream has been reached.

By analyzing the data captured by the SocketRead event, profiling tools can identify potential bottlenecks or performance issues related to socket read operations in the Java application.

Field Type Description

address string Remote Address
port int Remote Port
timeout long: millis Timeout Value
bytesRead long: bytes Bytes Read Number of bytes read from the socket
endOfStream boolean End of Stream If end of stream was reached

VirtualThreadPinned

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 19 21 22 23

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/VirtualThreadPinnedEvent.java

Category: Java Application

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in VirtualThreadPinnedEvent.java, JDKEvents.java, VirtualThread.java, and VirtualThreadPinnedEvent.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The VirtualThreadPinnedEvent is a Java Flight Recorder (JFR) event that is triggered when a virtual thread parks on its carrier thread. Here is the relevant information about the event:

  • This event is part of the "Java Application" category in JFR.
  • It is labeled as "Virtual Thread Pinned".
  • The event class is jdk.jfr.events.VirtualThreadPinnedEvent.
  • It extends the AbstractJDKEvent class.
  • The corresponding mirror event class is jdk.internal.event.VirtualThreadPinnedEvent.
  • The event records the fact that a virtual thread has parked on its carrier thread.
  • It can be used for profiling purposes to track the behavior and performance of virtual threads that are pinned to carrier threads.
  • The event does not have any additional fields other than the ones inherited from AbstractJDKEvent.
  • The event can be instantiated using the new VirtualThreadPinnedEvent() constructor.
  • The event can be started using the begin() method and committed using the commit() method.
  • Out of memory errors may occur when creating or committing the event instance.

Configuration enabled stackTrace threshold
default true true 20 ms
profiling true true 20 ms

Java Application Statistics

JavaThreadStatistics

default profiling startTime duration everychunk 11 17 21 22 23 graal vm

Category: Java Application / Statistics

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JavaThreadStatistics JFR event provides information about the active, daemon, accumulated, and peak thread counts in a Java application. It can be used for profiling and monitoring the thread usage in the application. The relevant fields of the event are:

  • activeCount: Number of live active threads including both daemon and non-daemon threads.
  • daemonCount: Number of live daemon threads.
  • accumulatedCount: Number of threads created and started since JVM start.
  • peakCount: Peak live thread count since JVM start or when the peak count was reset.

By analyzing these fields, developers can gain insights into how many threads are currently active, the number of daemon threads, the overall number of threads created and started, and the highest number of live threads reached during the JVM execution. This data can be used to optimize and tune the application's thread usage and identify potential bottlenecks or inefficiencies.

Configuration enabled period
default true 1000 ms
profiling true 1000 ms

Field Type Description

daemonCount long Daemon Threads Number of live daemon threads
accumulatedCount long Accumulated Threads Number of threads created and also started since JVM start
peakCount long Peak Threads Peak live thread count since JVM start or when peak count was reset

ClassLoaderStatistics

default profiling startTime duration everychunk 11 17 21 22 23

Category: Java Application / Statistics

No additional description available. Write your own and contribute it to jfreventcollector or directly to the OpenJDK.

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrPeriodic.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ClassLoaderStatistics event in JFR represents the statistics of class loaders in the JVM. It provides information about the following fields:

  • classLoader: The class loader responsible for loading classes.
  • parentClassLoader: The parent class loader of the current class loader.
  • classLoaderData: A pointer to the ClassLoaderData structure in the JVM.
  • classCount: The number of loaded classes by the class loader.
  • chunkSize: The total size of all allocated metaspace chunks for the class loader.
  • blockSize: The total size of all allocated metaspace blocks for the class loader.
  • hiddenClassCount: The number of hidden classes loaded by the class loader.
  • hiddenChunkSize: The total size of all allocated metaspace chunks for hidden classes.
  • hiddenBlockSize: The total size of all allocated metaspace blocks for hidden classes.

The ClassLoaderStatistics event can be used for profiling purposes to monitor the memory allocation and usage associated with class loaders. It provides insights into the number of classes loaded, the memory consumption of class loader metadata, and the presence of hidden classes. Profilers can leverage this information to identify potential memory bottlenecks and optimize the loading and unloading of classes.

Configuration enabled period
default true everyChunk
profiling true everyChunk

classLoader ClassLoader Class Loader Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
parentClassLoader ClassLoader Parent Class Loader Consider contributing a description to jfreventcollector.
classLoaderData ulong: address ClassLoaderData Pointer Pointer to the ClassLoaderData structure in the JVM
classCount long Classes Number of loaded classes
chunkSize ulong: bytes Total Chunk Size Total size of all allocated metaspace chunks (each chunk has several blocks)
blockSize ulong: bytes Total Block Size Total size of all allocated metaspace blocks (each chunk has several blocks)
hiddenClassCount long 15+ Hidden Classes Number of hidden classes
hiddenChunkSize ulong: bytes 15+ Total Hidden Classes Chunk Size Total size of all allocated metaspace chunks for hidden classes (each chunk has several blocks)
hiddenBlockSize ulong: bytes 15+ Total Hidden Classes Block Size Total size of all allocated metaspace blocks for hidden classes (each chunk has several blocks)

FinalizerStatistics

default profiling startTime endchunk 18 21 22 23

Category: Java Application / Statistics

Per class statistics about finalizers

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in jfrFinalizerStatisticsEvent.cpp using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The FinalizerStatistics event in JFR provides information about the finalization of objects in the Java Virtual Machine (JVM). It is relevant for profiling and can be used to analyze the behavior of finalizers in an application. Here is a concise explanation of its fields:

  • finalizableClass: Represents the class that overrides the finalize() method, indicating which objects are being finalized.
  • codeSource: Specifies the URL from where the class was loaded, providing information about the source of the finalizable objects.
  • objects: Indicates the number of objects on the heap that are eligible for finalization, providing insights into the memory usage of the application.
  • totalFinalizersRun: Tracks the total number of finalizers that have been executed since the JVM start, allowing analysis of the frequency of finalization activity.

By observing the values of these fields in the FinalizerStatistics event, developers and profiling tools can gain insights into the finalization behavior and potential bottlenecks in the application. This information can help identify objects causing unnecessary finalizations or excessive memory usage due to delayed finalization.

Configuration enabled period
default true endChunk
profiling true endChunk

Field Type Description
finalizableClass Class Class Overriding Finalize
codeSource Symbol Code Source URL from where the class was loaded
objects ulong Finalizable Objects on Heap Number of objects on heap that can be finalized
totalFinalizersRun ulong Finalizers Run Total number of finalizers run since JVM start

The X509CertificateEvent is a Java Flight Recorder (JFR) event that represents the details of an X.509 certificate parsed by the JDK. It is relevant for profiling purposes as it provides information about the certificate's attributes.

  • keyLength: the length of the key used in the certificate.
  • certificateId: the identifier of the certificate.
  • validFrom: the start date of the certificate's validity.
  • validUntil: the end date of the certificate's validity.

ContainerConfiguration

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 17 21 22 23

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ContainerConfigurationEvent.java

Category: Operating System

A set of container specific attributes

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ContainerConfigurationEvent.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ContainerConfiguration event in JFR is used for profiling container-specific attributes. It provides information about the configuration of a container and its resource limits. This event is relevant for profiling and monitoring containerized applications. The event contains the following fields:

  • containerType: Represents the type of container.
  • cpuSlicePeriod: Specifies the length of the scheduling period for processes within the container.
  • cpuQuota: Indicates the total available run-time allowed during each scheduling period for all tasks in the container.
  • cpuShares: Represents the relative weighting of processes within the container used for prioritizing the scheduling of processes across all containers running on the host.
  • effectiveCpuCount: Specifies the number of effective processors available to the container.
  • memorySoftLimit: Provides a hint to the operating system about the minimum required amount of physical memory for the container.
  • memoryLimit: Specifies the maximum amount of physical memory that can be allocated in the container.
  • swapMemoryLimit: Indicates the maximum amount of physical memory and swap space that can be allocated in the container.
  • hostTotalMemory: Represents the total memory of the host system running the container.

These fields can be used to analyze and optimize resource allocation and utilization within a container environment.

Configuration enabled period
default true beginChunk
profiling true beginChunk

Field Type Description
containerType string Container Type Container type information
cpuSlicePeriod long: microseconds CPU Slice Period Length of the scheduling period for processes within the container
cpuQuota long: microseconds CPU Quota Total available run-time allowed during each scheduling period for all tasks in the container
cpuShares long CPU Shares Relative weighting of processes with the container used for prioritizing the scheduling of processes across all containers running on a host
effectiveCpuCount long Effective CPU Count Number of effective processors that this container has available to it
memorySoftLimit long: bytes Memory Soft Limit Hint to the operating system that allows groups to specify the minimum required amount of physical memory
memoryLimit long: bytes Memory Limit Maximum amount of physical memory that can be allocated in the container
swapMemoryLimit long: bytes Memory and Swap Limit Maximum amount of physical memory and swap space, in bytes, that can be allocated in the container
hostTotalMemory long: bytes 20+ Container Host Total Memory Total memory of the host running the container

The ContainerCPUThrottling event in JFR (Java Flight Recorder) provides information related to container CPU throttling. This event is relevant for profiling and monitoring containerized applications. The event contains the following fields:

  • cpuElapsedSlices: Represents the number of time-slice periods that have elapsed if a CPU quota has been set up for the container.
  • cpuThrottledSlices: Represents the number of time-slice periods that the CPU has been throttled or limited due to exceeding the CPU quota.
  • cpuThrottledTime: Represents the total duration, in nanoseconds, that the CPU has been throttled or limited due to exceeding the CPU quota.

Profiling and analyzing these fields can help in understanding the impact of CPU throttling on the performance of containerized applications.

Configuration enabled period

profiling true 30 s

cpuThrottledSlices long CPU Throttled Slices Number of time-slice periods that the CPU has been throttled or limited due to exceeding CPU quota
cpuThrottledTime long: nanos CPU Throttled Time Total time duration, in nanoseconds, that the CPU has been throttled or limited due to exceeding CPU quota

ContainerMemoryUsage

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 17 21 22 23

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ContainerMemoryUsageEvent.java

Category: Operating System / Memory

Container memory usage related information

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ContainerMemoryUsageEvent.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ContainerMemoryUsageEvent is an event in Java Flight Recorder (JFR) that provides information about the memory usage in a container.

  • memoryFailCount: Number of times that user memory requests in the container have exceeded the memory limit. This field indicates the frequency at which memory requests have exceeded the allocated memory boundary in the container.
  • memoryUsage: Amount of physical memory, in bytes, that is currently allocated in the current container. This field represents the current memory consumption in the container.
  • swapMemoryUsage: Amount of physical memory and swap space, in bytes, that is currently allocated in the current container. This field includes both physical memory and swap space usage in the container.

Relevance to profiling and how to use it:

  • The ContainerMemoryUsageEvent provides important metrics for profiling memory usage within a container.
  • By monitoring the memoryFailCount field, developers can identify situations where memory requests are frequently exceeding the memory limit in the container, indicating potential performance issues.
  • The memoryUsage field gives insight into the current memory consumption in the container, enabling developers to monitor memory usage trends and track potential memory leaks or excessive memory usage.
  • The swapMemoryUsage field provides information about both physical memory and swap space usage in the container, which is valuable for profiling scenarios where memory and swap space have an impact on overall performance.

Overall, the ContainerMemoryUsageEvent plays a crucial role in profiling memory usage within a container, allowing developers to optimize resource allocation and identify potential memory-related performance bottlenecks.

Configuration enabled period
default true 30 s
profiling true 30 s

Field Type Description
memoryFailCount long Memory Fail Count Number of times that user memory requests in the container have exceeded the memory limit
memoryUsage long: bytes Memory Usage Amount of physical memory, in bytes, that is currently allocated in the current container

ContainerCPUUsage

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 17 21 22 23

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ContainerCPUUsageEvent.java

Category: Operating System / Processor

Container CPU usage related information

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ContainerCPUUsageEvent.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ContainerCPUUsage event in JFR is used to capture information related to CPU usage in a container environment. This event is relevant for profiling purposes as it provides insights into the amount of CPU time consumed by all tasks within the container.

Fields of the ContainerCPUUsage event:

  • cpuTime: Represents the aggregate time consumed by all tasks in the container.
  • cpuUserTime: Represents the aggregate user time consumed by all tasks in the container.
  • cpuSystemTime: Represents the aggregate system time consumed by all tasks in the container.

By analyzing the values of these fields, developers can gain visibility into how CPU resources are utilized within the container, enabling them to identify and optimize any performance bottlenecks.

Configuration enabled period
default true 30 s
profiling true 30 s

Field Type Description
cpuTime long: nanos CPU Time Aggregate time consumed by all tasks in the container
cpuUserTime long: nanos CPU User Time Aggregate user time consumed by all tasks in the container
cpuSystemTime long: nanos CPU System Time Aggregate system time consumed by all tasks in the container

ContainerIOUsage

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 17 21 22 23

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ContainerIOUsageEvent.java

Category: Operating System / File System

Container IO usage related information

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ContainerIOUsageEvent.java, and JDKEvents.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The ContainerIOUsage event in JFR provides information about the amount of block IO usage by a container. It is relevant for profiling and monitoring the IO activity of a container.

Fields:

  • serviceRequests: Number of block IO requests issued by the container.
  • dataTransferred: Number of block IO bytes transferred to/from the disk by the container.

By capturing this event, developers can analyze the IO usage of containers and identify potential performance bottlenecks or resource usage patterns.

Configuration enabled period
default true 30 s
profiling true 30 s

Field Type Description
serviceRequests long Block IO Request Count Number of block IO requests to the disk that have been issued by the container
dataTransferred long: bytes Block IO Transfer Number of block IO bytes that have been transferred to/from the disk by the container

ProcessStart

default profiling startTime duration stackTrace 15 17 21 22 23

Source src/jdk.jfr/share/classes/jdk/jfr/events/ProcessStartEvent.java

Category: Operating System

Operating system process started

Auto generated description experimental

The following is generated automatically by evaluating the generation of the event in ProcessStartEvent.java, JDKEvents.java, ProcessBuilder.java, and ProcessStartEvent.java using an LLM, so it might not be accurate, read more about this experiment at the related blog post.

The JFR event ProcessStart is used to track the start of an operating system process. This event is relevant for profiling purposes and provides information about the process, such as its process ID (pid), the directory in which it was started (directory), and the command used to start the process (command).

The event is part of the Operating System category and can be labeled as "Process Start" (jdk.ProcessStart). It can be used to gain insights into process execution and behavior during profiling, troubleshooting, or monitoring scenarios.

Key points:

  • The ProcessStart event captures information about operating system processes being started.
  • It provides fields such as pid, directory, and command to identify and analyze the started processes.
  • By enabling and collecting ProcessStart events, you can gather valuable information for profiling and understanding the behavior of your system's processes.

Note: The provided code snippets are only given as context and are not directly related to the explanation.
